VThis is a talk about sugar and cancer.
p4
aVI became interested in sugar when I was in college.
p5
aVNot this kind of sugar.
p6
aVIt was the sugar that our biology professors taught us about
p7
aVin the context of the coating of your cells.
p8
aVMaybe you didn't know that your cells are coated with sugar.
p9
aVAnd I didn't know that, either,
p10
aVuntil I took these courses in college,
p11
aVbut back then \u2014
p12
aVand this was in, let's just call it the 1980s \u2014
p13
aVpeople didn't know much about why our cells are coated with sugar.
p14
aVAnd when I dug through my notes, what I noticed I had written down
p15
aVis that the sugar coating on our cells is like the sugar coating
p16
aVon a peanut M and M.
p17
aVAnd people thought the sugar coating on our cells
p18
aVwas like a protective coating
p19
aVthat somehow made our cells stronger or tougher.
p20
aa(lp21
VBut we now know, many decades later,
p22
aVthat it's much more complicated than that,
p23
aVand that the sugars on our cells are actually very complex.
p24
aVAnd if you could shrink yourself down to a little miniature airplane
p25
aVand fly right along the surface of your cells,
p26
aVit might look something like this \u2014
p27
aVwith geographical features.
p28
aVAnd now, the complex sugars are these trees and bushes \u2014
p29
aVweeping willows that are swaying in the wind
p30
aVand moving with the waves.
p31
aVAnd when I started thinking about all these complex sugars
p32
aVthat are like this foliage on our cells,
p33
aVit became one of the most interesting problems that I encountered
p34
aVas a biologist and also as a chemist.
p35
aVAnd so now we tend to think about the sugars
p36
aVthat are populating the surface of our cells
p37
aVas a language.
p38
aVThey have a lot of information stored in their complex structures.
p39
aa(lp40
VBut what are they trying to tell us?
p41
aVI can tell you that we do know some information
p42
aVthat comes from these sugars,
p43
aVand it's turned out already to be incredibly important
p44
aVin the world of medicine.
p45
aa(lp46
VFor example, one thing your sugars are telling us
p47
aVis your blood type.
p48
aVSo your blood cells, your red blood cells, are coated with sugars,
p49
aVand the chemical structures of those sugars determine your blood type.
p50
aVSo for example, I know that I am blood type O.
p51
aVHow many people are also blood type O?
p52
aVPut your hands up.
p53
aVIt's a pretty common one,
p54
aVso when so few hands go up, either you're not paying attention
p55
aVor you don't know your blood type, and both of those are bad.
p56
aa(lp57
V(Laughter)
p58
aa(lp59
VBut for those of you who share the blood type O with me,
p60
aVwhat this means is that we have this chemical structure
p61
aVon the surface of our blood cells:
p62
aVthree simple sugars linked together to make a more complex sugar.
p63
aVAnd that, by definition, is blood type O.
p64
aa(lp65
VNow, how many people are blood type A?
p66
aVRight here.
p67
aVThat means you have an enzyme in your cells
p68
aVthat adds one more building block,
p69
aVthat red sugar,
p70
aVto build a more complex structure.
p71
aVAnd how many people are blood type B?
p72
aVQuite a few.
p73
aVYou have a slightly different enzyme than the A people,
p74
aVso you build a slightly different structure,
p75
aVand those of you that are AB
p76
aVhave the enzyme from your mother, the other enzyme from your father,
p77
aVand now you make both of these structures in roughly equal proportions.
p78
aVAnd when this was figured out,
p79
aVwhich is now back in the previous century,
p80
aVthis enabled one of the most important medical procedures in the world,
p81
aVwhich, of course, is the blood transfusion.
p82
aVAnd by knowing what your blood type is,
p83
aVwe can make sure, if you ever need a transfusion,
p84
aVthat your donor has the same blood type,
p85
aVso that your body doesn't see foreign sugars,
p86
aVwhich it wouldn't like and would certainly reject.
